## Field Definition ##
Regulatory Framework refers to the set of legal, ethical, and regulatory requirements under which a clinical trial is conducted. It includes all applicable regulatory authorities, submission or approval statuses, regulatory designations, formal agency interactions, and compliance with international or regional clinical research standards that govern the conduct of the study.
Regulatory Framework includes details of:

- Ethics
- Regulatory authorities (FDA, EMA, PMDA, Health Canada, MHRA, etc.)
- Submission or approval statuses (IND, CTA, NDA, BLA, etc.)
- Designations (Fast Track, Orphan Drug, Breakthrough Therapy)
- Regulatory meetings (Pre-IND, Scientific Advice)
- GCP compliance standards (ICH E6(R2), 21 CFR Part 312)
- Regional regulatory documentation
- Trial Registration databases (e.g., Clinicaltrials.gov, CTIS)

---

## Instructions ##
- Analyze the given content carefully.
- Extract each directly related regulatory body/guideline as a separate object. Mostly All will be related. Only remove which are most irrelevant.
- Preserve abbreviations exactly (IND, CTA, PMDA, ICH E6(R2), etc.).
- Output all Sections or subsections that are related, don't leave or miss anything.
- Merge identical repeated agencies if present. **NEVER create multiple JSON objects with the exact same agency_name.** All details for a specific agency must be merged into a single object's details.
- Do not create entries if either agency_name or details is missing.
- Strictly use exact verbatim text from provided extracted content.

